{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T19:41:50.280113+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T19:41:50.613605+00:00", "id": 19670501, "conceptrecid": "19670500", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670501", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670500", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19670501", "metadata": {"title": "Early-life maltreatment predicts adult stress response in a long-lived wild bird", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670501", "publication_date": "2018", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Persistent phenotypic changes due to early-life stressors are widely acknowledged, but their relevance for wild, free-living animals is poorly understood. We evaluated effects of two natural stressors experienced when young (maltreatment by adults and nutritional stress) on stress physiology in wild Nazca boobies (\n              Sula granti\n              ) 6\u20138 years later, an exceptionally long interval for such studies. Maltreatment as a nestling, but not nutritional stress, was associated years later with depressed baseline corticosterone in females and elevated stress-induced corticosterone concentration [CORT] in males. These results provide rare evidence of long-term hormonal effects of natural early-life stress, which may be adaptive mechanisms for dealing with future stressors.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Grace, Jacquelyn K.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Anderson, David J.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/3227a97b1ab8363621f419f4d38cad36", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/7846e3373b8c149e8c1a6ebe5a8c81daf000eeec9bddc019cff92b8c5491386d", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/H9BKYYT4", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/54